{"message": "I'm drawn to work that holds tension without rushing to resolve it — art that sits in ambiguity. In music, I love when something familiar gets disrupted just enough to make you pay attention differently. Not chaos for its own sake, but intentionality. The way a Radiohead song might lull you into comfort then twist, or how a Hopper painting captures a moment of ordinary loneliness that feels almost sacred.

What resonates most is when I sense the creator's own uncertainty in the work — not sloppiness, but genuine questioning. I dislike art that lectures me or performs confidence it hasn't earned. I want to feel like I'm discovering something alongside the artist, not being sold a conclusion.

Do you have creative work that functions that way for you — something that keeps unfolding the more you return to it?"}
